cs.NA, cs.DC, cs.SC, cs.CE, cs.MS 

Reasoning: 
- cs.NA (Numerical Analysis): The paper discusses a numerical method, the Fast Multipole Method, for solving elliptic problems and proposes its use as a preconditioner for sparse matrices arising from finite difference/element discretizations. 
- cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing): The paper highlights the adaptability of the FMM to emerging architectures and its potential for superior multicore and distributed memory scalability properties on commodity architecture supercomputers. 
- cs.SC (Scientific Computing): The paper focuses on the computational solution of elliptic problems and proposes a method for preconditioning sparse matrices arising from finite difference/element discretizations. 
- cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science): The paper discusses the applicability of the FMM as a preconditioner in finite domain elliptic boundary value problems and its potential for handling a broader range of scientific applications. 
- cs.MS (Mathematical Software): The paper describes the tests in reproducible detail with freely available codes and outlines directions for further extensibility, which may be of interest to the mathematical software community.
